0:{"rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"page-wrap","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"className":"page-back","href":"/#research","children":[["$","svg",null,{"width":"16","height":"16","viewBox":"0 0 16 16","fill":"none","children":["$","path",null,{"d":"M10 3L5 8L10 13","stroke":"currentColor","strokeWidth":"1.5","strokeLinecap":"round"}]}],"Back"]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"article-hero","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"research-meta","style":{"marginBottom":16},"children":[["$","span",null,{"children":"February 2026"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"·"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"8 min read"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"·"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"Systems Architecture"}]]}],["$","h1",null,{"children":"The Case for Vertical Integration"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"article-content","children":[["$","p","0",{"children":"The conventional wisdom in technology product development favors horizontal specialization: use the best-in-class tool for each layer, integrate at well-defined interfaces, and swap components as better options emerge."}],["$","p","1",{"children":"We've come to believe this is often the wrong model — particularly for companies building at the intersection of hardware and software, or anyone where performance and user experience are existential concerns."}],["$","h2","2",{"children":"What Vertical Integration Actually Means"}],["$","p","3",{"children":"Vertical integration doesn't mean building everything from scratch. It means owning the interfaces between layers, so you can optimize across them. Apple doesn't just make the chip and the OS — they design the chip for the OS. That cross-layer optimization is where the real performance gains live."}],["$","h2","4",{"children":"The Interface Tax"}],["$","p","5",{"children":"Every abstraction layer has a cost. This is well understood in performance-critical systems. What's less discussed is the product design cost: when you don't own an interface, you can't change its behavior. You're constrained to what the interface exposes."}],["$","p","6",{"children":"This matters enormously in product development. The most interesting features often require cooperation across layers that were designed independently. Vertical integration makes this possible."}],["$","h2","7",{"children":"When to Apply It"}],["$","p","8",{"children":"Vertical integration has real costs — higher engineering investment, more surface area to maintain. It's the right choice when the experience you're building genuinely requires cross-layer optimization, and when you have the engineering capacity to maintain what you build."}]]}]]}],null,["$","$L3",null,{"children":["$","$4",null,{"name":"Next.MetadataOutlet","children":"$@5"}]}]]}],"isPartial":false,"staleTime":300,"varyParams":null,"buildId":"pyGCzhn3iTGD2__OF9WVo"}
